<DOCNO>FT924-5184</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CK0B0AGHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921127
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / Survey of FT Traveller, Paris (15): Where to dance the night
away - Parisian nightclubs slide in and out of fashion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN the early hours of every morning a gaggle of people gathers on rue du
Bourg-l'Abbe, a narrow street among the fashion showrooms and sweat shops of
Sentier, the rag trade area of central Paris.
They queue there morning after morning, whatever the weather, to try to get
into Les Bains, the night club that has for years dominated the Parisian
night scene. Any truly fashionable Parisian will roll their eyes at the
mention of Les Bains, mutter something about it being passe and advise you
to go to one of the mercurial one-nighters that are held in different venues
all over the city.
Passe or not, other clubs open and close in Paris, but Les Bains goes on. It
is still the place that Chanel chooses for its fashion parties, where the
fashion industry holds the Venus awards (the fashion designers' own prizes
for each season's collections) and where Roman Polanski, and almost every
other fashionable film director, hold their post-premiere parties.
No-one with any sense would go to Les Bains to dance. The dancefloor is tiny
with a distractingly low ceiling and Parisians, who tend to be as aggressive
about staking their claim on the dance floor as about poaching parking
spaces, have very sharp elbows. The music at Les Bains is satisfactory, but
not sensational. The Folies Pigalle, the hastily converted music hall on
place Pigalle, has a bigger and better dance floor as does la Locomotive,
the triple-storey club on boulevard de Clichy, which also has far funkier
music.
Nor would anyone choose Les Bains for its food, its drink (both predictably
over-priced) or even its decor, which, with its video monitors and shabby
chic seats looks like any one of half a dozen Manhattan night clubs.
Although Les Bains does score high aesthetic points for the ceiling of its
(unisex) toilets upstairs, a sea of pink plastic roses, tres Jeff Koons.
But Les Bains, like all really long-lasting night clubs, comes top of the
class for voyeurism. It is probably still the only place in Paris where you
are virtually guaranteed to see a sprinkling of super-models, fashion
designers, film directors and visiting American movie stars (Sylvester
Stallone turned up with a posse of black leather-clad body guards) on any
one night among the army of suburbanites on the dancefloor.
OTHER clubs flicker in and out of fashion. Niel's, which opened last autumn
on avenue des Ternes, is popular with the film crowd, as is Le Comptoir on
rue Vauvilliers beside Les Halles centre with the fashion scene.
But people still queue on rue Bourg-l'Abee. The only hitch is getting in.
One of the ruses with which Les Bains, like all really longlasting night
clubs, has protected its reputation is by operating a supremely snobby door
policy. Night after night, or, more accurately morning after morning, there
are humiliating scenes as people plead with Marilyn, the formidable door
person, to be allowed in.
There is a simple solution. If your idea of a fun night out in Paris does
not include shivering on the pavement outside a night club that you may or
may not eventually be allowed to go in to, then telephone Les Bains on 4887
0180, and book a table at the restaurant. You can then sail past Marilyn and
eat your meal before fighting for a few spare square inches on the Les Bains
dance floor.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page X
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-5185</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CK0B0AGGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921127
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / Survey of FT Traveller, Paris (13): Golden rules - Business
etiquette, introductory lunches play a pivotal part in forging corporate
liaisons and doing deals. But the social side of business still has a
special salience.
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN Bernard Arnault, one of France's most ambitious businessman, arrived at
Christian Dior, the fashion house he bought in the mid-1980s, he was asked
out to lunch by one of his new colleagues.
'Why?' replied Mr Arnault. 'What would we have to talk about?'
The story may be apocryphal - most stories about Mr Arnault are - but the
incredulity with which it is still repeated in Paris business circles serves
to highlight the importance of that most sacrosanct of France's corporate
rituals, le dejeuner, otherwise known as lunch.
In a city where whom you know or, more specifically, who graduated with you
from your Haute Ecole, is just as important as what you know, the social
side of business still has a special salience. Lunches play a pivotal part
in forging corporate liaisons and doing deals.
But unfortunately for the foreign visitor to Paris, the written and
unwritten rules on what you should and should not say over the lunchtable
are not only very strict, but incredibly complicated.
The golden rule to remember is that no-one ever, ever actually dirties their
hands by doing business during lunch. Broadly speaking there are three types
of business lunches.
The first, which appears wantonly time-wasting to Anglo-Saxon eyes, is the
'introductory' meal at which you make contact with someone with whom you
might want to do business in the future, but at which you would not dream of
discussing anything concrete.
The second lunch is more constructive. This is the type of meal at which a
new venture may be discussed although, yet again, no-one in Paris would ever
expect to actually clinch a deal over the lunchtable. If the time has come
to sign on the dotted line, you will have to wait until you go back to the
office after the meal. You can then move on to the third and final form of
dejeuner, celebrating a deal that has already been done.
The only time you are expected to talk about business is during dessert. In
the meantime you are allowed to discourse on everything from world affairs,
to the state of the European economy and the latest amours of the Monegasque
royal family (whom the French generally find more interesting than the
British equivalent) - anything in fact but the reason for the lunch.
Finally, you have to brace yourself for a lengthy lunch in Paris - two hours
is the absolute minimum, three is generally seen as more polite - and also
for an assault on the arteries.
Four courses - hors d'oeuvre, plat du jour, cheese and dessert with coffee -
are the norm, although it is just permissible to skip the cheese and get
straight down to business.
As for the delicate question of language. The French business elite is in a
cosmopolitan mode at the moment. Most senior executives speak at least one
other language, usually English, reasonably fluently, and possibly two or
three others. However ropey your French it is always considered courteous to
at least try to speak it to your new contacts, even if you do breathe a deep
sigh of relief when they break into your own tongue.
The English are at a distinct advantage in that the French language
apparently sounds particularly charming when spoken with an English accent,
just as English does when spoken by the French. The poor Spaniards lose out,
as French is said to sound particularly harsh when spoken with Spanish
tones.
But wherever you come from, you must never forget that it is very rude to
call your new French contact tu, unless they invite you to do so first.
In the meantime, you should always use the formal vous.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page X
</PAGE>
