<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / Survey of FT Traveller, Paris (11): An endangered species -
Traditional cafes / These familiar French institutions are closing at the
rate of 5,000 a year and the more famous survivors have become objects of
nostalgic fascination for tourists
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHENEVER the French newspapers, or television news crews, are short of a
story they rush off to one of the tiny tabac bars, the cafes au coin along
the Parisian back streets, dust down a few Robert Doisneau photographs, and
publish yet another obituary of the cafe.
The French cafe, with its prim patronne and zinc comptoir, is an endangered
species. There are now only 70,000 cafes in France, compared with 510,000 in
their early 1900s heyday. The decline continues with at least 5,000 more
cafes closing each year.
The cafe au coin is a victim of modernity. Almost every innovation in the
20th century has hit it in one way or another. The decline of heavy industry
has taken a toll on its blue collar clientele. The spread of takeaway sushi
bars means that fewer Parisians pop out for snacks at their local cafes.
Rising living standards have made cafe staff far stroppier about working
long hours for low pay.
Anyone who cherishes the idea of reliving one of Doisneau's 1950s cafe
scenes on their next visit to Paris is probably doomed to disappointment.
The grand cafes, Aux Deux Magots on boulevard Saint-Germain and the Cafe de
la Paix on boulevard Haussmann by the Opera, are now teeming with tourists
and most of the cafes aux coins, once Art Nouveau idylls, are smoke-filled
monuments to 1960s retail redesign with vinegary vins and formica-like food.
There are still a few really pretty cafes with authentic interiors dotted
around the city, although they have probably survived by accident rather
than design. Le Cochon a l'Oreille on rue Montmartre has weathered the
disappearance of its original customers, the workers from the nearby Les
Halles fruit and vegetable market. It now serves basic, but tasty bistro
fare from its sumptuous ceramic-lined interior to the new community of
office workers, and journalists who have converged on Les Halles.
The tiny cafe-tabac a few streets away on the corner of place des
Petits-Peres at the back of place des Victoires, serves even simpler fare.
But it does sell reasonable wines and excellent espresso from an unspoilt
Art Nouveau interior. There is also a sprinkling of pleasant cafes and bars
along rue Vieille du Temple in the Marais and on the side streets straddling
rue de l'Universite in Saint-Germain.
If you still long to while away an hour over a cafe-creme at a grand
Parisian cafe, the best choice is Cafe de Flore on boulevard Saint-Germain.
Cafe de Flore's coffee and carpaccio are delicious, and there are not quite
so many tourists as at Aux Deux Magots a few doors away.
Alternatively you could plump for one of dozens of salons du the that have
popped up across Paris in recent years. The rise of the salons du the is one
of the main reasons for the demise of the Parisian cafe, as they tend to
offer fresher food - generally salads, tartes and cakes - in prettier
surroundings than the traditional cafes au coin.
A Priori The in the lovely old Galerie Vivienne by place des Victoires is an
excellent example, with delicious salads and tartes, served on simple wooden
tables with pretty wicker chairs. The best tables are outside on the mosaic
floor of the galerie, where you can watch the sunlight shafting through the
glazed roof in the summer, or, if you are very lucky, snowflakes settling on
snowy winter days. The only hitch is that A Priori The is packed every
lunchtime - so arrive early.
Tea Follies on place Gustave-Toudouze just below Pigalle is another classic
Parisian tea room serving traditional teas with scones, laced with local
delicacies such as its delicious savoury tarts and chicken pies. Le Loir
dans la Theiere is another old-fashioned tea room on rue des Rosiers in the
heart of the Marais, where you can sink down into the battered armchairs to
choose from a delicious selection of cakes, salads and tartes (the
pascualina spinach tarte is the house speciality) among its Alice in
Wonderland wall murals.
If you are in too much of a hurry to contemplate languishing at a cafe, the
best places in Paris for really speedy snacks are the branches of Lina's,
the chain of deluxe sandwich bars, on rue Etienne Marcel along from Place
des Victoires, on rue Marboeuf off the avenue Champs-Elysees and on the
third floor of the Galeries Lafayette department store.
The system of service at Lina's can seem a little bizarre to the
uninitiated. You queue at the counter to give your order to one of the
sandwich makers (most of whom seem to have been selected for their looks
rather than their skill at spreading moutarde on your jambon only to then
queue again to pay at the cashdesk. You then return to your original queue -
hopefully elbowing your way through to the front - to collect up your order
from the sandwich-maker.
It is all worthwhile. Lina's does make the very best sandwiches in Paris.
Its chunky pain pave is particularly tasty, especially when rounded off by
the house speciality, a Lina's chocolate brownie.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
