<DOCNO>FT924-5193</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CK0B0AF7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921127
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / Survey of FT Traveller, Paris (3): Impact on a grand scale -
Francois Mitterrand has made a personal imprint on the city's appearance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NIGHT and day a small troop of armed guards are stationed beside the
barricades at either end of the rue de Bievre running down to the river from
the boulevard Saint-Germain in Paris fifth arrondissement.
The guards are there because rue de Bievre is the private address of
President Francois Mitterrand. He is rarely there. For the 11 years of his
presidency he has spent most of his time at the Elysee Palace, but he is
still fond of reminiscing about his time back at rue de Bievre when he would
pop along the street to the local bistrot.
Francois Mitterrand was born at Jarnac in Charente but has spent most of his
adult life in Paris, first as a journalist, then a lawyer and finally a
politician. From the moment he became president he made it absolutely clear
that he planned to make his mark on the city - and to make it last.
The Paris of 1981, when the socialists swept on to the streets to celebrate
the election of the first socialist president of the Fifth Republic, was a
very different city from the Paris of today.
The most visible legacies of the Mitterrand era are the glossy Grands
Projets - the luminous Louvre Pyramid, the giant Arc de la Defense and the
glittering Bastille opera house - that are now part and parcel of the
cityscape.
The culture of Paris has changed too. The old-fashioned ouvrier socialism of
the early Mitterrand era was quickly supplanted by the groovy gauche caviar
ethos of the rest of his regime.
Le gauche caviare is out of tune with the more ascetic mood of the early
1990s as the opinion polls attest. Francois Mitterrand now faces the
challenge of redefining socialism for the 1990s if he is to avoid an
enforced return to his old home on rue de Bievre after the next presidential
elections.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-5194</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CK0B0AF6FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921127
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / Survey of FT Traveller, Paris (4): Relentless self-publicist
 -Jacques Chirac has ruled the French capital since he became mayor in 1977
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE chain-smoking mayor, with his perpetual smile and his pinstripe suits,
is part and parcel of the city's politics. Yet Jacques Chirac, now nearing
60, has made no secret of the fact that he sees Paris as little more than a
platform to the serious business of national power.
Chirac began his career as a civil servant, working his way through the
ministerial ranks until 1974 when he became prime minister under President
Valery Giscard d'Estaing. Two years later he resigned to nurture his own
national powerbase as head of the neo-Gaullist RPR.
He and his old presidential mentor have since fought over, and disastrously
divided, the conservative right, as illustrated by the damaging split over
this autumn's Maastricht referendum. So far they have proved spectacularly
successful at squashing their younger would-be successors although, as their
critics suspect, they may be damaging their own parties' electoral prospects
in the process.
Jacques Chirac is still best known outside France for his second stint as
prime minister during the cohabitation era from 1986 to 1988. Cohabitation
came to an abrupt end in 1988 when the RPR suffered its worst electoral
defeat in the 30 year history of the Fifth Republic courtesy of Jean-Marie
Le Pen's extreme right wing Front Nationale, whose racist policies split the
party and stole its votes.
The head of the RPR, a relentless self-publicist who conducted his last
presidential campaign from a travelling circus tent, has been left to bide
his time back at the opulent Hotel de Ville, firing off the odd offensive at
President Mitterrand, until the next elections come along.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-5195</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CK0B0AF5FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921127
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / Survey of FT Traveller, Paris (2): Bordering on the
burlesque - Political battles / Jacques Chirac, mayor of Paris, has been
waging war against France's head of state ever since Francois Mitterrand
trounced him in the 1981 presidential elections
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Hotel de Ville with its Disneyesque towers, turrets and tricolors on the
right bank of the Seine has for a very long time played a pivotal part in
the politics of Paris.
Danton, Robespierre and Marat, the lynchpins of the French Revolution,
decamped there in 1792 to turn it into their seat of government. But in 1871
the Hotel de Ville was ransacked by the angry mobs that swept through the
city in the early days of the Paris Commune.
The Hotel de Ville, sparkling in neo-Renaissance splendour with its
illuminated fountains and shimmering chandeliers, is now the scene of
another political struggle in its current role as the campaign headquarters
of Jacques Chirac, the neo-gaullist who has been mayor of Paris since 1977,
in his bitter battle against Francois Mitterrand, France's socialist
president.
Mr Chirac has been waging war against France's head of state ever since
Francois Mitterrand trounced him in the 1981 presidential elections. The
battle between them has become all the fiercer since the uncomfortable era
of cohabitation between 1986 and 1988 when they wrestled for power on the
national stage, while Jacques Chirac played prime minister to Francois
Mitterrand's president.
The two men have clashed over everything from the rights and wrongs of
military intervention in Bosnia-Hercegovina, to whether the French state
should have chopped down the trees on Quai Branly, to who was to stand
closest to the Queen of England at the photocalls for her official visit to
Paris.
All too often the battles have bordered on the burlesque. The mayor's
assaults on the Grands Projets, the ambitious architectural programme
initiated by the president and Jack Lang, his faithful arts minister and
another Chirac bete noir, are a fine example.
Almost every new architectural scheme, from IM Pei's Louvre Pyramide, to
Dominique Perrault's Tres Grande Bibliotheque, has been treated to an attack
 -on aesthetic, social or financial grounds, often on all three - from the
Hotel de Ville only to be defended with a carefully cultivated air of
insouciance from the president.
At first glance, President Mitterrand appears to hold the winning hand if
only because central government still controls many aspects of the
management of Paris, including public transport. Mr Chirac has been left to
drum up as much publicity as he can for the few areas left under his aegis -
ranging from the enormous electronic information boards he has plastered all
over the city (relaying details of the time, traffic jams and the weather)
to his 'poop-scooping' campaign against dog dirt.
The Hotel de Ville's power has also been eroded by the socialists'
decentralisation programme which has been implemented throughout France but
could scarcely have been better designed to curb Jacques Chirac's authority.
These reforms started six years ago with the creation of the Ile de France
region, an elected body that now adminstrates the area in and around Paris
in tandem with the council. They continued in 1990 with the appointment of a
state-selected prefet to represent the government in the region.
But the wily mayor has battled back. The Ile de France region is in the
sympathetic hands of a Chirac loyalist. Equally important, the city
council's budget at FFr18.7bn for 1992 is still twice as big as that of the
region. The prefet, Christian Sautter, is a Mitterrand man and was once
senior adviser to the president. But he has forged a sound relationship with
the Ile de France loyalist and, in practice, there are relatively few
serious differences of opinion on strategic issues between the various
governing bodies.
CONTEMPORARY Paris is a prosperous place. New buildings have been flung up,
old buildings lovingly restored and the city's statues glisten after their
recent regilding. In the early hours of the morning the streets are crammed
with the apple green vans of the city council, scooping up litter, hosing
down pavements, sweeping the roads and even polishing the street signs.
During the Mitterrand era Paris has gained 137km of new railway track, four
times more than London, and 500km of motorway to London's 250km. A fourth
express rail route is now under construction and a fifth is in the pipeline.
There are also plans for a fourth ring road and for five subterranean
motorways.
This investment seems to have done little to tackle the city's appalling
traffic problems. Parking is still a nightmare. It is almost impossible to
find a legal parking space in central Paris at night. The pavements of the
grands boulevards are littered with abandoned cars. The huge subterranean
car parks built by the city council in the late 1980s have had little
impact. The only consolation is that things would almost certainly be even
worse without them.
Yet, almost all the comparative studies between contemporary Paris and
London come out in the French capital's favour. Paris wins higher marks for
transport and planning in a recent British government report, while London
scores on culture and greenery. When it comes to public service
infrastructure, Paris has a clear advantage. The London Underground,
according to the report, is slower, dirtier, less efficient and more
dangerous than the Paris Metro.
The chief criticism levelled at Jacques Chirac is that, like Mayor Ed Koch
in New York, he has gentrified his city to such a degree that the centre is
now an enclave for the affluent, with the disadvantaged shipped out to the
potentially explosive poverty belt of the suburbs.
But it is the government, not the city council, that usually gets the blame
whenever the suburbs erupt in sporadic bursts of urban unrest. And Jacques
Chirac has yet to lose an election. He, and his loyalists, have been
returned to power by poll after poll. Mr Chirac is only likely to leave the
Hotel de Ville on his own terms. In other words he will only do so if he
finally triumphs in a presidential election so that he can swap the towers
and turrets of the Hotel de Ville for the 18th century grandeur of the
Elysee Palace.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
