<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / Britain braced for EC budget row: UK proposes 'restrained
increase' to break spending deadlock
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL and SHEILA JONES AND PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK braced itself for a furious reaction from its European Community
partners at a meeting of ministers in Brussels today after putting forward
proposals yesterday to break the nine-month deadlock over the future
financing of the EC.
At a 'conclave' of foreign and finance ministers, Mr Douglas Hurd, the
foreign secretary, and Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, will present
proposals envisaging 'a more restrained increase' in EC spending than a
recent proposal from EC Commission president Mr Jacques Delors.
Britain is also refusing to yield to mainly German pressure to give up its
annual rebate, worth about Pounds 2bn, from its EC contributions. While the
UK will discuss reformulating the way the money is paid back, the scale of
the rebate is not negotiable.
Britain has proposed a seven-year agreement that would freeze the upper
limit of the EC budget at the present 1.2 per cent of Community gross
national product for three years from the start of next year, before raising
it in stages to 1.25 per cent by 1999.
According to UK Treasury figures, the British plan would lift the EC budget
to Pounds 61bn or Ecu 79.3bn at 1992 prices by 1999 from Pounds 47bn this
year against Mr Delors' plan to boost the budget to Pounds 64bn after seven
years.
Britain wants to force other member states - notably Germany - to clarify
their stance on the budget well ahead of the Edinburgh summit in two weeks.
British diplomats are aware that if the presidency cannot advance the debate
on the EC budget, it risks an embarrassing deadlock at the summit after what
many of its partners consider a disastrous EC presidency.
If EC leaders cannot reach a decision on the budget at the summit,
negotiations for the admission of new EC members - one of the British
presidency's central objectives - will also have to be delayed.
Germany and the Netherlands are expected to back the British plans for a
more modest EC budget, but poorer member states will oppose any package that
would leave them worse off than under the Commission's current plans for EC
spending, known as the Delors II package.
The British presidency is prepared to face fierce criticism from Ireland,
Spain, Greece and Portugal, which are seeking funds to encourage economic
convergence with the wealthier EC members. The so-called 'cohesion' funds in
the Delors II proposals have been cut from Ecu15bn to Ecu12.25bn under the
British plans. UK officials stressed yesterday that this would still amount
to a quite substantial increase in funding compared with the 1988-92 budget
period.
Row looms over UK plan to resolve EC budget, Page 2
