<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Class changed The controller of BBC2, Alan Yentob, seems to have decided
that the first two hours of Friday evening should be devoted to what might
be called 'heritage television'. Thus the 1965 children's puppet series
Stingray (6.00) is followed at 6.25 by another series from the same year,
The Man From UNCLE, the United Network Command for Law Enforcement whose
main agents were Napoleon Solo and Ilya Kuryakin, played by Robert Vaughn
and David McCallum.
At 7.15 comes an old Dr Who story starring Jon Pertwee which the BBC had
junked. Luckily some fanatic somewhere had kept a monochrome recording and
the BBC has now 'colourized' this so that it can be re-shown. Dr Who began
in 1963, but the oldest series of the lot in this early evening blitz is
What The Papers Say which began in 1956 and looks like it.
If you liked 'Civvies' with its violence and sentimentality, and 'Prime
Suspect' with its unusually nasty murder plot and hatred of men, and
'Widows' with its amoral attitude towards female criminals, then you may
well like Framed (9.00 ITV) since all these works are by Lynda La Plante.
</TEXT>
