<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / Technology: Ten light bulbs for the price of one - Worth
Watching
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DELLA BRADSHAW
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The chandeliers at Chatsworth House and the light bulbs in the Goat Inn
public house near Peterborough both exploit a British design for increasing
the life of the ordinary light bulb.
The Bulbsaver, developed by Microcel, of Peterborough, is a tiny device
installed behind the wall switch. The chip-on-a-circuit reduces the
electrical surge which occurs when the light is switched on and which
weakens the filaments in the bulb. The designers say the life of bulbs
should be increased 10 times.
At Pounds 4 per unit the Bulbsaver will be most widely used where it is
difficult to replace bulbs - in belisha beacons or railway signals - or
where one switch controls a large number of bulbs. Microcel: UK, 0778
347214.
</TEXT>
