<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / Bupa rates move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUPA, the UK's biggest private health insurer, yesterday announced that it
will not increase small-business customers' insurance premiums in January,
thereby stemming the drift upwards in rates over the past four years.
Customers of Bupa's CompanyCare scheme, available to businesses with fewer
than 100 employees, will face average rate rises of 7.2 per cent on policies
renewed through to next spring, reflecting an increase announced last May.
Bupa said rates for bigger corporate subscribers, whose premium rates
directly reflect the value of claims during the year, are not affected by
yesterday's move.
Individual customers renewing their BupaCare programme will face a total
rise of 14.7 per cent, reflecting changes in July and an average 6.1 per
cent increase from January.
Bupa has negotiated a number of deals with hospital groups - reducing the
cost of hospital care - and has also persuaded more subscribers to use
day-care surgery.
</TEXT>
