<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / Pay review body considers options
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE OF the main independent review bodies for public-sector pay is still
considering whether it is worthwhile preparing the annual report on its
sector since being stripped of its ability to recommend pay rises.
The doctors' and dentists' review body, like four of the five review bodies,
has been asked not to make a recommendation this year. The teachers' pay
review body was set up by statute and is obliged to make a recommendation.
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, said in his Autumn Statement that
public-sector pay settlements for next year would be restricted to a maximum
of 1.5 per cent. He asked the review bodies to amend their remits for the
coming year and to make no recommendations about overall levels of pay, fees
or allowances for April 1 1993.
The doctors' and dentists' review body was asked to report on 'miscellaneous
matters' including general practitioners' fee scales and merit awards for
consultants.
The review body at first said that such a report would be 'inappropriate'.
But after correspondence with the government it has been reconsidering its
response and will make a final decision on Wednesday.
The other review bodies have said they are prepared to accept restricted
briefs.
</TEXT>
