<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / Severe cuts in services feared
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL authority associations reacted with dismay to the rate support grant
settlement and tight capping rules announced yesterday, claiming that they
would lead to severe cuts in local services.
Mr Jeremy Beecham, leader of Newcastle upon Tyne council and chairman of the
Labour-controlled Association of Metropolitan Authorities, said the
'unrealistic' spending targets plus capping would leave 'local government
services in the worst state I've known them in my 25 years in local
government'.
The Association of County Councils pointed to the government's inconsistency
in allowing central government spending to rise by 6.6 per cent over this
year's actual expenditure, while local spending is to be restricted to a 0.4
per cent increase.
The government's failure to provide additional relief for business
ratepayers - who face a 3.5 per cent increase - was criticised by the
Federation of Small Businesses. 'All government help and rebates are aimed
at council-tax payers, yet the uniform business rate will raise twice as
much as council tax,' it said.
A warning of severe cuts in vital public services and of job losses even if
there was a public-sector pay freeze came from Labour MPs listening to Mr
Howard's statement, while Tory backbenchers complained about the
'inefficiencies' of Labour councils.
There were cross-party complaints about the way the government calculates
how much it thinks each local authority needs to spend.
Though MPs generally welcomed the government's move to incorporate some 1991
census data in drawing up its standard spending assessments, Tory and Labour
backbenchers were seriously concerned about the way these worked in
practice.
Mr Howard emphasised that the precise mechanism of distributing the grant
was still provisional, and undertook to look carefully at further
representations from councils about the way they were affected by the
system.
</TEXT>
