<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / Council tax bills depend on local spending curbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT'S ability to keep the average council tax bill in England
down to Pounds 500, the target announced yesterday, will depend critically
on ministers keeping firm control over local spending.
To that end, Mr Michael Howard, environment secretary, has notably tightened
the rules allowing him to cap local council spending. But their
effectiveness will depend on the success of councils in keeping their pay
settlements for next year within the government's target range of 0 per cent
to 1.5 per cent for the public sector.
Applying the government's multiplier to the eight council tax bands, which
divide properties by their value in April 1991, gives the average bills in
the table, provided councils spend at or below government targets.
The government believes that the great majority of councils, if they keep
the lid on pay, should have no difficulty in keeping within its estimates of
spending needs ('standard spending assessments'). SSAs have been increased
by an average of 3.1 per cent on last year's, allowing for the transfer of
responsibilities to and from local government. Its rate support grant
funding for councils is to increase by 3.7 per cent.
However, the local government associations claim that the government's
Pounds 41.17bn target for total spending in 1993-94 represents only a 0.4
per cent increase on what councils are actually spending this year. They
also point to the fact that pay settlements for part of next year are
already agreed at above 3.7 per cent, a funding increase which in any case
includes money (like that to cushion the council tax) that cannot be applied
to existing services.
Most councils are now spending at or above SSA, which is also used as the
basis for capping. Of England's 39 county councils, only five are this year
spending more than 1 per cent below SSA, while two are more than 1 per cent
above. Barely one or two are expected to budget significantly below SSA next
year. Much therefore will depend on the ruthlessness with which the
government applies its capping rules for next year.
The capping rules are more generous than those announced for Scottish
authorities earlier in the month, but will still cause severe problems for
the large inner-city authorities spending well above SSA.
Under the rules, authorities planning to spend less than 1 per cent above
SSA will be restricted to a 2.5 per cent increase in total spending. That
will have the effect of capping most county councils to a spending increase
of about 3 per cent. However, authorities already more than 1 per cent above
SSA - including most cities - will be capped at much smaller increases.
Those planning to spend more than 10 per cent above will be capped at a 0.5
per cent increase on this year's bud-get.
Mr Howard claimed that councils need not raise any more from council tax
payers than they are taking from poll tax payers. Most analysts believe the
skills of a magician will be needed to achieve that.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 11
</PAGE>
