<DOCNO>FT924-5331</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CK0B0AB1FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921127
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / Steelmaking gear may be sold
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER and JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH STEEL is negotiating with an unnamed Indonesian company for the sale
of plant and equipment from the Ravenscraig steelworks in Scotland, which
closed in June with the loss of 1,200 jobs.
The potential purchaser would transport the equipment to Indonesia to make
steel for the Far Eastern market, which is expected to be the most important
growth area in the world steel market over the next few years.
Reports that the steel would then be exported back to the UK were being
discounted yesterday.
The dominant Indonesian steel company is state-owned Krakatau Steel, but
there are smaller private producers and conglomerates such as Bakrie and
Brothers which have steel interests.
It is believed the Indonesian company is likely to be interested in
steelmaking machinery and control equipment rather than blast furnaces.
The equipment could include the hot strip mill, commissioned in 1962 and
closed early last year. The mill was regarded as an efficient strip producer
but too small to be economic except at very high throughput levels.
The Scottish National party said: 'This gives the lie to British Steel's
claim that Ravenscraig was clapped out or uncompetitive.'
But Dr Jeremy Bray, Labour MP for Motherwell South, which includes the
plant, said: 'Ravenscraig is never going to operate again so the sale of the
plant doesn't affect Motherwell.'
</TEXT>
