<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / Big cement groups switch from rail to roads
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BLUE CIRCLE and Castle Cement, two of British Rail's biggest freight
customers, yesterday said they were switching nearly 500,000 tonnes of
freight a year from rail to road because of BR price increases.
The move will result in an extra 20,000 road journeys a year by fully laden
38-tonne articulated trucks. Other railfreight customers say they are
considering similar moves.
News of the shift came as Charterail, the pioneering private-sector
railfreight distributor which ceased trading in August, announced that it
had gone into liquidation with the loss of 120 jobs.
Charterail had earlier accused BR of prompting its collapse by charging too
much for use of its locomotives and tracks. The company's failure has put an
estimated 10,000 truckloads of freight a year on the road. Charterail's
failure and the loss of the cement business are the most significant
indicators yet that the government is not prepared to intervene to stop the
continuing drift of freight from rail to road.
They will also heighten fears that privatisation will increase the drift
because charges to railfreight users will rise as the railways are put on a
more commercial footing.
Castle Cement said yesterday that it was switching 210,000 tonnes of cement
a year from rail to road. Mr Jonathan Dale, director of logistics, blamed
BR's Trainload Freight for raising prices to uneconomic levels when the
recession was bringing road transport costs down.
'To make our rail operations viable we would need a cut of 75 per cent in
the freight rates on offer - that's the sort of gap that has opened up,' he
said.
Blue Circle said it was moving 275,000 tonnes of cement a year to road
because of BR's rising prices. A further 210,000 tonnes a year was
transferring to road because of changing distribution patterns, and the
company was reviewing its other railfreight flows.
Imperial Chemical Industries, Britain's biggest manufacturing company, said
it was also reviewing its options.
The Freight Transport Association said BR was losing freight to the roads
because it was raising prices to cut losses in the run-up to privatisation,
and that had left its freight charges uncompetitive. The transport
department said there was no connection with privatisation. Some of BR's
freight operations had been losing money for some time and it was a
commercial decision by BR to tackle them. BR could not be contacted because
part of its telecommunications network had broken down.
</TEXT>
