<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / Union chief to quit early
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR LESLIE CHRISTIE, the 53-year-old general secretary of the National Union
of Civil and Public Servants, is to stand down six years early, his union
said yesterday.
Mr Christie would have faced re-election within the next 18 months, and most
Civil Service union officials believe he would have been successful. He took
over as leader of the 100,000-strong NUCPS when the Society of Civil and
Public Servants, the mainly lower-management grade Civil Service union which
he led, merged in 1987 with the smaller Civil Service Union.
The pressures on Mr Christie have been intense in recent months. The union
faces radical changes in the Civil Service including devolved pay bargaining
and contracting-out.
It is also having to restructure itself to accommodate the Civil Service
reforms at a time when it is making large losses. In the year to December
1991 it recorded a deficit of more than Pounds 500,000 on income of Pounds
10.8m and this year is expected to be worse.
Mr Christie was not available for comment.
</TEXT>
