<DOCNO>FT924-5340</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CK0B0ABSFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921127
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / Birt admits BBC's share of funding will fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BBC has reconciled itself to attracting a third of the radio and
television audience and winning about a third of broadcasting funding as
commercial broadcasting expands, Mr John Birt, who will become
director-general next month, said yesterday.
Launching the BBC's vision of its future, Mr Birt denied he was planning an
orderly retreat for the corporation.
It was simply a realistic assessment of what was likely to happen, and there
was no point trying 'Canute-like' to hold back the tide of competition or
plunging downmarket in pursuit of ratings.
'The average British household will still watch or listen to BBC services
for something like 24 hours a week,' Mr Birt said. The BBC at present has
between 42 per cent and 45 per cent of audiences.
'The BBC in the late 90s will continue to be a significant and positive
force in everyday life in Britain,' he said.
Flanked by Sir Michael Checkland, the departing director-general, and Mr
Marmaduke Hussey, the BBC chairman, Mr Birt yesterday outlined the BBC's
view of its future.
The document argues that a single integrated corporation should survive and
provide all its present services, funded almost entirely by a universal
licence fee.
The main changes will be in the type of programme offered, the efficiency
with which they are made and the corporation's accountability to the
audience in everything it does.
Because all households pay the licence fee the BBC will continue to serve
all groups and work in all programme areas. But increasingly it will seek to
complement commercially funded broadcasting by providing services which will
be put under pressure or not provided elsewhere in a more competitive
broadcast market.
The BBC, Mr Birt said, would stick to its traditional task of providing a
rich mix of programmes which entertain, educate and inform, but 'in ways
which press forward; which break new ground; which pioneer; which innovate
and challenge the audience; which are marked by intelligence, invention and
wit; which strive for quality and excellence'.
The BBC would move away from making or transmitting programmes of the kind
provided abundantly elsewhere or making programmes which are derivative or
imitative.
Mr Birt said that 'significant sums' would be released for programmes from
the review of overheads and the initiative giving BBC producers the right to
buy services in the outside market.
In future the BBC will set itself four roles to complement the commercial
sector:
Providing comprehensive and impartial news and information across a range of
broadcasting outlets, with serious information programmes staying in
prime-time slots.
Supporting and stimulating the development and expression of British culture
and entertainment.
Guaranteeing the provision of programming and services that create
opportunities for education.
Stimulating the communication of cultures and ideas between Britain and
abroad.
BBC1 will be the main national network television channel delivering
programmes to a wide audience, while BBC2 should be more innovative,
addressing different audience groups.
Radio 1 and Radio 2 would survive, but the BBC would develop 'distinctive
and innovative services', he said.
There is a commitment to the BBC orchestras but there will be discussion of
'ways in which they can play a full part in the national pattern of
orchestral funding and provision'.
The BBC also plans to be more accountable to its audience both with the
value for money that it provides and on dealing with complaints.
A well-defined framework of objectives and performance indicators will be
created, against which management will be held accountable. It will involve
much more detailed research on who is watching what and how appreciative the
audiences are.
A further document is expected soon setting out a more clear division of
responsibilities between the BBC governors and the board of management.
Mr Birt promised that the future BBC would be a 'lean, efficient,
enterprising, unbureaucratic BBC,' dedicated to quality and focused firmly
on programme creativity and innovation.
With the publication of the document - the product of more than 15 internal
committees - the debate on the renewal of the BBC's royal charter which runs
out at the end of 1996 is officially under way.
Extending Choice: The BBC's Role in the New Broadcasting Age. BBC,
Broadcasting House, London W1A 1AA. Pounds 2.95.
</TEXT>
