<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / Tighter rules on assets promised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ACCOUNTING Standard Board's forthcoming paper on off-balance-sheet
finance will restrict the scope for assets to be removed from the balance
sheet, the FT Financial Reporting Conference was told yesterday.
Mr Graham Stacy, senior technical partner of Price Waterhouse and an ASB
member, said its draft will allow de-recognition of an asset only when:
No significant rights to the asset are retained.
Any risk retained is immaterial in relation to the variation in benefits
likely to occur.
Mr Andrew Lennard, assistant technical director of the ASB, said the board
was considering taking a less restrictive approach to debt maturity
following the hostile reaction to its treatment in the discussion document
on capital instruments.
He said it was likely to permit short-term debt to be reported as long-term
where the same lender is firmly committed to provide further finance on the
same terms.
Mr Allan Cook, the ASB technical director, said the board was conducting
tests with about a dozen large companies to determine the continuing value
of goodwill - the difference between the net assets and the purchase price
of an acquisition.
That will help the ASB determine how to treat goodwill in its future
proposals on accounting for business combinations.
Mr John Shaw, a member of the Financial Reporting Council and chairman of
the conference, said the ASB had identified a tension in enlisting support
for greater disclosure and transparency in accounts from City analysts.
He said this was because they in part made their livelihood from translating
complex financial information.
