FT  27 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: MPs to get free vote on Sunday bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EMPLOYEE PROTECTION emerged as a potential flashpoint last night as the
government unveiled its plans for a bill to implement the reform of Sunday
trading in England and Wales.
Confirming that MPs would be offered a free vote on the core issue of
whether restrictions to Sunday trading should apply, Mr Kenneth Clarke, home
secretary, pledged that the envisaged bill would contain government clauses
to protect 'existing' shopworkers from being compelled to work on a Sunday.
But he skated around Labour demands that protection should additionally be
given to future employees who objected to Sunday working. His 'instinct'
would be not to aim at a set of regulations applicable solely to those
employed in shops, he said.
It later emerged that the government was not ruling out seeking to whip its
employee protection provisions through the Commons.
MPs are to be offered a choice between a set of options for Sunday shopping
ranging from full-scale deregulation to a tightening of existing laws.
Full deregulation - the choice favoured by Mr Clarke - would be on the
present Scottish model, while the most restrictive option would be along the
lines advocated by the Keep Sunday Special campaign.
A third option, proposed by the Shopping Hours Reform Council, is included.
This would allow small shops to open on Sundays essentially without
restrictions, while permitting larger outlets to open for up to six hours.
It is uncertain whether the bill will come before the Commons in the present
parliamentary session.
The drafting of legislation must await a decision by the European Court on
whether the present law was overridden by the free-trade articles of the
Treaty of Rome. Mr Clarke said yesterday that this ruling was now unlikely
to be available before January.
The government has been committed to reform of the Sunday trading laws since
1987 but has been reluctant to legislate after its last attempt was defeated
by a Conservative backbench rebellion in 1986.
For Labour, Mr Tony Blair, the shadow home secretary, welcomed the proposals
if they were handled in a 'sensible' manner and said the challenge was to
present 'a lasting reform' which ended 'the present de-regulation through
anarchy'.
The 'nub' of the issue was whether all employees - present and future -
would be subject to the voluntary principle and entitled to premium payments
for Sunday working.
</TEXT>
