<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: School fees ruling raises wider
issues - Robert Rice and Andrew Jack on how Hansard was cited to clarify
legislation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE and ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER many years of dispute, lawyers and accountants were yesterday
digesting the impact of the Law Lords' decision in the Pepper vs Hart case.
At issue was whether schoolmasters were permitted to pay fees at marginal
cost for their children attending the school at which they taught, without
them being taxed as a benefit. Had they lost, thousands of employees could
have faced changes in benefits provided by their employers.
By ruling in their favour, the Law Lords have raised far wider
constitutional questions over the extent to which ministerial statements in
Hansard - the official report of parliamentary debates - can be used to help
clarify the intention of a piece of legislation.
The Law Lords said it was common ground that concessionary fees more than
covered the additional cost to the school of educating the taxpayers'
children and that the childrens' education at reduced fees was a taxable
benefit under the 1976 Finance Act.
The crucial question was how much should be treated as an emolument - the
cash equivalent of the benefit. The taxpayers argued that the only expense
incurred by the school 'in or in connection with' the education of their
children was the additional or marginal cost to the school.
The Revenue argued that the expense incurred in or in connection with the
provision of education for children of the taxpayers was the same as the
expense for all other pupils. Therefore the expense of educating any one
child was a proportionate part of the cost of running the whole school.
The Law Lords said the cost to the employer of providing an 'in-house
benefit' for the employee (in this case concessionary education) depended on
whether the courts could look behind the language of the statute to reports
of parliamentary proceedings in order to determine the true legislative
intention of parliament.
The taxpayers would win if the courts were allowed to refer to parliamentary
material as an aid to statutory interpretation, as was clear from a reading
of Hansard covering parliamentary debates on the 1976 act and from
statements made by the financial secretary at the time.
But if the courts were not entitled to refer to parliamentary material, a
literal interpretation of the 1976 act meant the Revenue's argument would
succeed.
Under present law there is a general rule (the exclusionary rule) dating
back to 1769 that references to parliamentary material as an aid to
statutory construction are not allowed.
Although the courts' attitude to this rule had varied, they had made
reference to reports which lead to legislation. But until 1989 there was no
modern case in which a court had looked at parliamentary debates as an aid
to construction.
In 1989 the House of Lords made big inroads by looking at a minister's
parliamentary words to help them decide a statutory regulation's meaning.
Mr Anthony Lester, QC for the teachers, argued that where the words of a
statute were ambiguous or obscure or were capable of giving rise to an
absurd conclusion it should be legitimate to look at the parliamentary
history to identify the intention of parliament. But he said the exclusion
rule should not be relaxed entirely. The attorney-general argued that the
rule had a sound constitutional and practical basis and should not be
relaxed. The use of Hansard would constitute a 'questioning' of the freedom
of speech or debate as it would involve an investigation of what a minister
meant by the words he used, and would inhibit him in what he said by
attaching legislative effect to his words.
The Law Lords disagreed. The only real objection to a relaxation of the rule
was that legal advisers would waste hours at the expense of litigants
researching parliamentary intent. This would raise the cost of litigation.
But Lord Browne-Wilkinson said it was easy to overestimate the cost of
research. Hansard would show whether the minister said anything significant,
making further research pointless.
The Law Lords therefore said the rule should be relaxed to allow reference
to parliamentary material where:
Legislation was ambiguous, obscure or led to an absurdity.
The material relied or consisted of one or more statements of a minister or
other promoter of a bill.
The statements relied on were clear.
Looking behind the language of the 1976 act it was clear the teachers must
win the appeal.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-5350</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CK0B0ABIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921127
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / Taxing the Monarchy: Queen could face king-sized life
insurance policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Personal Finance Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF the Queen does agree to pay inheritance tax, her advisers Peat Marwick
could be faced with a lot of work. The planning could involve writing the
biggest life insurance policy in history.
No definitive figure has been reached on her wealth, but if her investments,
art and jewellery collections and her private homes are included, it could
be as much as Pounds 6.5bn. Since inheritance tax is 40 per cent on estates
of more than Pounds 150,000, that could leave her facing a bill for around
Pounds 2.5bn.
The good news is that clever tax planning could reduce that bill to
virtually zero. The first thing the Queen must do is write a will, since
elaborate tax planning is impossible without one.
The next step is to get the Treasury to give National Heritage exemption to
all the art, jewellery and stately homes. According to Mr David Rothenberg,
senior tax partner at accountants Blick Rothenberg, this would mean that
portion of the Queen's wealth could pass to her heirs tax-free.
A second bonus for the Queen is that, in the last Budget, agricultural land
 -a significant element of her wealth - was granted 100 per cent relief from
inheritance tax - with some exemptions.
The biggest remaining element of the Queen's wealth is her investment
portfolio. Here, Mr Rothenberg says she could follow a more elaborate
strategy.
First, she could sell all her shares and buy them back immediately - known
as bed-and-breakfasting - before she becomes eligible for capital-gains tax.
This would establish a new, high base level for any future capital-gains tax
liabilities.
Then she could give away the investments to her relatives. These gifts would
be subject to capital-gains tax, but only on any gains made after the
bed-and-breakfast process.
Provided the Queen then lives for seven years, these gifts would be free
from inheritance tax. To cover that period, however, the Queen could then
take out a massive life insurance policy, says Mr Rothenberg. This would be
written in trust for her heirs, and thus the proceeds of the policy would
not themselves be subject to inheritance tax.
If the Queen dies within the seven-year period, the proceeds of the policy
could be used to meet the inheritance-tax liability.
The Queen has other opportunities to save tax. Money left to a spouse is
tax-free, although this would only postpone the problem until Prince
Philip's death.
A more populist solution would be giving the money away. Gifts of up to
Pounds 3,000 each year can be made to a particular person, and be exempt
from inheritance tax.
On top of this, small gifts of up to Pounds 250 can be made to any number of
individuals without incurring tax. On death, gifts to charities, political
parties and some other non-profitmaking organisations are exempt.
So this Christmas, never mind the begging letters to Santa Claus, send them
to Buckingham Palace.
</TEXT>
