<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / School fees ruling preserves perks for thousands
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK and ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TENS OF THOUSANDS of em-ployees have been saved from losing their perks at
work by a landmark ruling against the Inland Revenue from the House of Lords
yesterday.
The decision will allow many companies to structure their benefits without
fear of incurring additional costs. Many have delayed tax planning while
awaiting the judgment.
The case, Pepper v Hart, concerned the reduced school fees paid in 1983 for
their own children by 10 teachers at Malvern School, including Mr John Hart,
a senior master.
But, it had enormous implications for many employers offering benefits to
their staff. Those affected would have included employers with subsidised
canteens, sports facilities or travel, and those able to buy goods at a
discount.
British Airways confirmed last night that it was one of several companies
and professional firms which contributed to a Pounds 100,000 'fighting fund'
to help in the appeal. If the case had been lost, its employees might no
longer have been able to buy airline tickets at 10 per cent of the retail
price.
The teachers at Malvern argued that they should only be taxed on any
difference between the reduced fees they paid for their own children and the
marginal cost of providing this education - such as meals, laundry and
books. The Inland Revenue claimed the teachers should be assessed for tax on
any difference existing between the fees they paid and the average cost of
the fees.
The Revenue said yesterday it would be issuing a statement shortly on the
implications of the judgment.
It still has the option of seeking new legislation which could push for
average cost on employee benefits to apply in the future.
Mr Hart said: 'It's an absolute rout. There was tremendous interest from the
boys, wishing us good luck. I was bullish at every point. I'm going to buy a
new car next week.'
The law lords' statement was described last night as a landmark decision by
Ms Leslie Ferrar, a tax partner at KPMG Peat Marwick, because it said
ministers' speeches in parliament could be taken into account when
interpreting the law.
The ruling means lawyers may have to consult Hansard to understand
ministers' intentions when they were debating legislation, even though their
ideas may not have been reflected clearly in the letter of the law.
School fees ruling, Page 8
</TEXT>
