<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / UK Company News: Banks agree rescue deal for Rosehaugh
Stanhope schemes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANKS OWED an estimated Pounds 1.25bn have agreed a five-year refinancing
package with Rosehaugh Stanhope Developments, the owner of two of London's
largest office schemes.
The deal, which involves around 50 banks, was signed earlier this week. It
was crucial to the survival of the company which is jointly owned by
Rosehaugh and Stanhope, two of the UK's hardest hit property developers.
Separately, an announcement is expected in the next few weeks about the
acquisition by UBS Phillips &amp; Drew of the building it occupies and financed
in RSD's Broadgate office complex. UBS, which is owed Pounds 200m by RSD, is
negotiating the purchase of the building in order to secure the repayment of
its debt next April.
RSD is also in talks with Credit Lyonnais, another Broadgate tenant, about
the sale of its building. RSD is expected to make further write-downs in the
value of its assets, which comprise the Broadgate and Ludgate office schemes
in the City of London, when it publishes its accounts for the year to June.
In the year to June 1991, its net asset value fell by 15 per cent to Pounds
341.2m.
Rosehaugh and Stanhope have been particularly badly hit by the depression in
the London office market, where values have fallen by two-thirds from the
peak of the market three years ago. Merger talks between the two companies
were called off earlier this year.
RSD's management is becoming increasingly independent of either parent
company, although this will not involve a change to RSD's ownership
structure. Earlier this year, Rosehaugh agreed a refinancing of its Pounds
310m debt until January 1994. Stanhope is currently discussing the
restructuring of its debts with its banks, led by Barclays.
The banks have been prepared to support companies like Rosehaugh, Stanhope
and RSD because they are reluctant to sell assets at distressed prices in
the severely depressed London office market.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 22
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-5410</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CK0B0ADLFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921127
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 NOV 92 / The Lex Column: Thyssen
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Given the deteriorating German economy, it is natural to wonder whether
yesterday's dividend cut from Thyssen will be its last. After all, British
Steel cut its dividend last year only to omit its interim this. Germany may
not yet be facing a UK-style recession, but its steel producers confront
some particular handicaps compared with European rivals whose currencies
have devalued. Still, things would have to get much worse for Thyssen's new
dividend, which is nearly twice covered, to come under threat.
Yesterday's preliminary - and incomplete - figures suggest that operating
profits held up better than many expected. The 33 per cent fall in 1991-92
net profit will have been struck only after as yet undisclosed provisions
for steel rationalisation which should boost net profits by some DM200m from
1993-94. The question for the current year is how much other businesses will
contribute to offset continuing weakness in steel.
Budd will clearly benefit from any US recovery, and there may be a modest
gain from a stronger dollar. But the German market for capital goods will
hardly be anything other than depressed. Even a secure net yield just below
4 per cent thus looks low. Earnings will doubtless snap back with economic
recovery, but that will need help from the Bundesbank.
</TEXT>
