FT  26 NOV 92 / US army drops Star Wars order
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US Army cancelled yesterday a Dollars 594m (Pounds 393.3m) research
contract with McDonnell Douglas to develop and test a tracking system for
the Strategic Defence Initiative, or Star Wars, anti-ballistic missile
defence, Agencies report from Washington.
The army said the shrinking defence budget forced it to withdraw the
contract from the nation's biggest defence company and four big
subcontractors.
The move is a further sign of financial distress and delay for the proposed
defence programme. The SDI has suffered a succession of financial setbacks
in Congress in recent years. Legislators this year slashed from Dollars
5.4bn to Dollars 3.8bn President George Bush's request for 1993 research
funds.
Army officials said the contract was won by McDonnell Douglas in 1988 and
that about Dollars 200m of the funds had already been spent.
