<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: Minister hints at road tax increase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ACTION TAKEN in next year's spring Budget to recoup the revenue lost through
the abolition of the five per cent car tax which took effect on November 12
could result in the annual vehicle excise duty being increased from Pounds
110 to Pounds 141.
This possibility was acknowledged by Mr Anthony Nelson, economic secretary
to the Treasury, in the Commons last night when MPs approved the Car Tax
(Abolition) Bill.
He stressed that the full range of motoring taxation - leaded and unleaded
petrol, and diesel fuel as well as the vehicle excise duty - would be
considered by Mr Norman Lamont,the chancellor, before determing how to
effect the recoupment.
If the recoupment burden fell entirely on fuel, it could result in an
increase of 2.2p per litre in the price of leaded petrol and 1.8p in the
price of unleaded petrol and diesel fuel, he added, saying he could not
anticipate the chancellor's decision.
Mr Andrew Smith, a Labour Treasury spokesman, asked why the government was
assessing the cost of abolishing the tax at Pounds 750m rather than the
Pounds 628m figure that would be arrived at after accounting for the extra
VAT proceeds the government would rake in from a forecast 70,000-vehicle
increase in sales.
'Recouping the revenue in this way does not actually give any extra fiscal
stimulus,' he said, adding that Labour nonetheless welcomed the abolition.
'It just shifts the burden of tax from the shoulders of those who can afford
new cars to those who cannot.'
Mr Smith said that a second Labour concern was that abolition of the tax
would not provide 'the scale of stimulus that the motor industry needs.'
Consumer confidence remained very shaky owing to the fear of unemployment
and outstanding debt, he said.
Even if the forecast 70,000 sales increase did indeed materialise, that
would still leave sales 29 per cent lower than in 1989.
For the Liberal Democrats, economic spokesman Mr Alan Beith urged the
government to consider placing the recoupment burden on company cars.
</TEXT>
