<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 92 / Letter: Facilities to relieve road congestion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr STEFAN B TIETZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Conclusions drawn in your leader, 'Cars, congestion and pollution'
(November 20), were shared by a conference held in London last week, which
considered Greater London's transport problems. There was one important
difference. There was considerable agreement that road pricing is inevitable
and other forms of constraint would be needed.
It was not, however, felt that there would ever be enough space for all the
roads necessary in suburbs or towns. It is therefore essential that
alternatives are put in place which would allow for the adequate movement of
people and goods by the time that such constraints come into full force.
The needs that were identified are, first, improved radial and cross-London
services, and, second, an orbital ring railway around London. A ring railway
would link the suburbs which now generate over 50 per cent of the total car
traffic in greater London. A further need is for local services such as
light rail and tram links.
Only with such facilities in place would there be opportunities to
rationalise road traffic without serious harm to London's economy.
Stefan B Tietz,
S B Tietz and Partners,
14 Clerkenwell Close,
London EC1R 0PQ
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
