<TEXT>
Zinc and Nickel were the strongest markets at the London Metal Exchange
yesterday, and their firmness helped to steady other metals. Traders said
that ZINC had been underpinned recently by trade buying, which emerged again
today, taking the three months delivery position above Dollars 1,080 a tonne
and touching off short-covering and stop-loss buying orders. At the close
the three months price was quoted at Dollars 1,089.50 a tonne, up Dollars
24.75 on the day. Chinese buying was cited as the main factor lifting NICKEL
prices, which rose for the sixth successive trading day. The three months
position closed at Dollars 5,515 a tonne, up 39 on the day and Dollars 200
from last week's 5-year low. At the London Futures and Options Exchange
COFFEE prices continued this week's retracement, with the January position
ending Dollars 5 lower at Dollars 944 a tonne. Dealers said talks on a new
pact to support prices at the International Coffee Organisation continued to
be monitored, although progress, as expected, was slow.
